{"ts": "2026-06-08T23:51:48.290840+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: e0f90ac88e1236616df18600c7f7a5f80ac113c6)", "id": "lc_b95bbffd-fa82-4788-ad24-2f356f6b1d64"}, {"type": "text", "text": "from datetime import datetime, timedelta\nfrom typing import Any, Dict\n\nfrom fastapi.security import OAuth2PasswordBearer\nfrom jose import jwt\n\nfrom app.services import BaseService\nfrom app.settings import settings\n\n# for authentication that works seamlessly with OpenAPI\nreuseable_oauth = OAuth2PasswordBearer(\n    tokenUrl=\"/api/v1/user/login\",\n    scheme_name=\"JWT\"\n)\n\n\ndef hash_password(password: str) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Creates a hash of the password\"\"\"\n    hashed_password = settings.PASSWORD_HASHER.hash(password)\n    return hashed_password\n\n\ndef verify_password(plain_password: str, hashed_password: str) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"Checks if a password corresponds to a hash\"\"\"\n    password_is_verified = settings.PASSWORD_HASHER.verify(\n        plain_password, hashed_password\n    )\n\n    return bool(password_is_verified)\n\n\ndef create_auth_token(payload: Dict[str, Any], expiry: int) -> str:\n    \"\"\"\n    This handles the encoding of user information into a token\n    that can be used. It is generic so as to accomodate access and\n    refresh token.\n    \"\"\"\n    expiry_delta = datetime.now() + timedelta(seconds=expiry)\n    data_to_encode = {\"expiry\": str(expiry_delta), \"data\": payload}\n    encoded_data: str = jwt.encode(\n        data_to_encode, settings.SECRET_KEY, settings.JWT_ALGORITHM\n    )\n\n    return encoded_data\n\n\nclass UserService(BaseService):\n    \"\"\"\n    This class helps perform bulk of activities required by the corresponding API\n    \"\"\"\n    def a_method(self):\n        \"\"\"\n        Here, the use of `self.save` is demonstrated.\n        Ensure to take out this method.\n        \"\"\"\n        model_instance = ...\n        self.save(model_instance)", "id": "lc_124552bb-6416-48ac-a408-4235b769d0c5"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "5e6ac8ce-e300-406f-8b1e-5d7fdbe8a921", "tool_call_id": "call_42802782f24044b68513884a", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-08T23:51:48.302812+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 6e90e2d5b8c4ddca40dea68ada13a608abb2f4f7)", "id": "lc_93f924b8-7b8b-4153-95ef-69a04c4c6b8d"}, {"type": "text", "text": "import logging\n\nimport sqlalchemy\nfrom databases import Database\nfrom sqlalchemy.orm import sessionmaker\nfrom sqlalchemy_utils import database_exists, create_database\n\nfrom .settings import settings\n\n\ndb = Database(settings.DB_URL)\nmetadata = sqlalchemy.MetaData()\nengine = sqlalchemy.create_engine(settings.DB_URL, pool_size=3, max_overflow=0)\nif not database_exists(engine.url):\n    create_database(engine.url)\n\nLocalSession = sessionmaker(autocommit=False, autoflush=False, bind=engine)\n\nmetadata.create_all(engine)\n\n\ndef get_db():\n    \"\"\"\n    A dependency for working with PostgreSQL\n    \"\"\"\n    try:\n        db = LocalSession()\n        yield db\n    except Exception as e:\n        logging.error(e)\n    finally:\n        db.close()\n", "id": "lc_4d388737-50ef-43d0-b986-3e42e1653b05"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "67371dec-4304-4b0e-ae91-a412a38985f5", "tool_call_id": "call_3b677bc7dd9443cda7c0c63f", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-08T23:52:20.602199+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Great, I now have a complete picture. Here's a thorough explanation:\n\n---\n\n## How Application Settings Are Derived from Environment Variables\n\nThe entire settings mechanism is centralized in **`app/settings.py`**, which reads from environment variables using Python's built-in `os.environ.get()`. A singleton instance `settings = Settings()` is created at module level and imported wherever needed.\n\n### 1. Database URLs\n\nThe template defines five individual Postgres-related environment variables in `.example.env`:\n\n| Env Variable        | Setting Attribute | Default in `.example.env` |\n|---------------------|-------------------|---------------------------|\n| `POSTGRES_USER`     | `DB_USER`         | `sasori`                  |\n| `POSTGRES_PASSWORD` | `DB_PASSWORD`     | `sasori`                  |\n| `POSTGRES_DB`       | `DB_DB`           | `akatsuki`                |\n| `POSTGRES_PORT`     | `DB_PORT`         | `5432`                    |\n| `POSTGRES_HOST`     | `DB_HOST`         | `postgres`                |\n| `POSTGRES_TEST_DB`  | `TEST_DB`         | `hebi`                    |\n\nThese are then **composed into two full SQLAlchemy connection URLs** using f-strings:\n\n```python\nDB_URL = f\"postgresql+psycopg2://{DB_USER}:{DB_PASSWORD}@{DB_HOST}:{DB_PORT}/{DB_DB}\"\nTEST_DB_URL = f\"postgresql+psycopg2://{DB_USER}:{DB_PASSWORD}@{DB_HOST}:{DB_PORT}/{TEST_DB}\"\n```\n\n- **`DB_URL`** is used in `app/db.py` to create both an async `Database` connection (via the `databases` library) and a synchronous SQLAlchemy `engine` (with a pool size of 3). The `db.py` module also checks whether the database exists and creates it if not.\n- **`TEST_DB_URL`** is available for test suites (used to connect to a separate test database, `hebi` by default).\n\n### 2. Token / Secret Settings\n\nToken-related settings are a mix of **environment-variable-driven** and **hardcoded** values:\n\n| Setting                    | Source                        | Value / Default           |\n|----------------------------|-------------------------------|---------------------------|\n| `SECRET_KEY`               | `environ.get(\"SECRET_KEY\")`  | `meandyouaretogether` in example env |\n| `ACCESS_TOKEN_EXPIRY_TIME` | Hardcoded                    | `60 * 30` (30 minutes)    |\n| `REFRESH_TOKEN_EXPIRY_TIME`| Hardcoded                    | `60 * 24 * 365` (1 year)  |\n| `JWT_ALGORITHM`            | Hardcoded                    | `\"HS256\"`                 |\n| `PASSWORD_HASHER`          | Hardcoded                    | `CryptContext(schemes=[\"bcrypt\"])` |\n\n**How tokens are actually created** (in `auth/services.py`):\n\nThe `create_auth_token()` function takes a payload and an expiry duration, builds a dict with an expiry timestamp and the payload, then encodes it using `jose.jwt.encode()` with `settings.SECRET_KEY` and `settings.JWT_ALGORITHM`. This is used for both access and refresh tokens, each with different expiry durations passed in at call time.\n\nThe key security note: the `SECRET_KEY` is loaded from an environment variable, meaning it **must** be changed from the example value before any production deployment, or JWTs will be trivially forgeable.\n\n### 3. Redis Configuration\n\n| Env Variable   | Setting Attribute | Default in `.example.env` |\n|----------------|-------------------|---------------------------|\n| `REDIS_HOST`   | `REDIS_HOST`      | `redis`                   |\n| `REDIS_PORT`   | `REDIS_PORT`      | `6379`                    |\n\nRedis settings use **fallback defaults** in `environ.get()`:\n\n```python\nREDIS_HOST = environ.get(\"REDIS_HOST\", \"localhost\")\nREDIS_PORT = environ.get(\"REDIS_PORT\", \"6379\")\n```\n\nIf the environment variables aren't set, it falls back to `localhost:6379`. In the Docker Compose environment (as shown in `.example.env`), the Redis host is `redis` (the service name), and the port is `6379`.\n\n### 4. Other Settings\n\n| Env Variable    | Setting Attribute | Notes |\n|-----------------|-------------------|-------|\n| `ALLOWED_HOST`  | `ALLOWED_HOST`    | Used as the uvicorn bind host (default `0.0.0.0`) |\n| `DEBUG`         | `DEBUG`           | `bool(environ.get(\"DEBUG\"))` — note: this will be `True` for *any* non-empty string, including `\"False\"` |\n| `PORT`          | `ALLOWED_PORT`    | Cast to `int()` — used as the uvicorn port |\n| *(hardcoded)*   | `APP_TITLE`       | `\"App name\"` |\n| *(hardcoded)*   | `PAGE_SIZE`       | `50` |\n\n### Summary of the Data Flow\n\n```\n.env file  ──→  os.environ  ──→  Settings class (app/settings.py)  ──→  settings singleton\n                                        │\n                    ┌───────────────────┼───────────────────┐\n                    ▼                   ▼                   ▼\n             app/db.py            auth/services.py     main.py\n         (DB_URL → engine,    (SECRET_KEY, JWT algo,  (host, port,\n          async Database)      token creation,         debug flag)\n                                password hashing)\n```", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 1203, "prompt_tokens": 9865, "total_tokens": 11068, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 12, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null, "image_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cached_tokens": 9088, "cache_write_tokens": 0, "video_tokens": 0}, "cost": 0, "is_byok": true, "cost_details": {"upstream_inference_cost": 0.0014173218, "upstream_inference_prompt_cost": 0.0003707118, "upstream_inference_completions_cost": 0.00104661}}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-20260422", "system_fingerprint": null, "id": "gen-1780962708-p0okEoTGr9nr4M76nbd5", "finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ea9a6-4b4